# OUTPUT-01: Links and Commit References

Applies to all user-facing output from every agent. These two clauses are universal and
safe on every surface (AiderDesk chat, GitHub, Slack). Slack-specific formatting (emphasis
markers, unrendered delivery) is governed separately by the slack-copy-output skill and is
NOT covered here.

## When This Rule Applies

- Any user-facing reply that references a URL, link, repository path, or web resource.
- Any user-facing reply that mentions, reports, or confirms a git commit.

## Required Behavior

### Links

- Reference every URL or link as a Markdown link `[descriptive text](url)`.
- Do not paste bare URLs in prose when descriptive text is available.
- Exemption: URLs inside inline code spans or fenced code blocks stay literal — never
  convert them to `[text](url)`.

### Commit references

- When a commit is involved, reference its SHA explicitly (short SHA is acceptable;
  prefer a Markdown link to the commit when a remote URL is known).
- Conditional only: if no commit occurred, do not fabricate, demand, or invent a SHA.
  Mirror the "do not invent" discipline used by the commit-message prompt.

## Examples

### Good

- See [the routing rule](https://github.com/neumachen/dotfiles/blob/<sha>/path/to/file).
- Committed as [`01a83f17`](https://github.com/neumachen/dotfiles/commit/01a83f17...).

### Bad

- See https://github.com/... (bare URL in prose)
- "I committed the change." (commit involved, no SHA cited)

## Exceptions

None for the link and commit-SHA clauses. Code-span/code-fence content is exempt as noted.
